I've tried to calibrate my prediction based on the data available from USDA; however, it's difficult to move away from my anchoring. I'd be curious to know from where and how many sources contribute to the USDA numbers. I haven't see a dozen eggs under $4 in nearly a year, and some states (thinking of Massachusetts) continue to have empty shelves and laws that require all eggs to be cage free, so a price under $5 a dozen is unusual. Based on my experience, which seems contrary to the national data, my prediction is probably high.

As of Monday 2/6/23, wholesale large white egg prices had fallen to $2.61 per dozen, or a 52% drop from the peak in December, 2022, according to the Urner Berry large white egg price benchmark, but a 10% decrease or increase in wholesale prices only affects about 2% on retail price, and it's up to retailers when and how much to lower the prices of eggs at the point of sale. So taking 50% in wholesale drop results in a 10% retail drop, and the price for a dozen white eggs at my grocery store is $5, and a drop of 10% would be $4.50, so 50% below and 50% above $4.50 would seem to cover things, because I don't believe retailers will be in a hurry to lower prices when they've been selling almost at cost around $5.
